><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub96.ezboard.com/usllackblader.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sllack Blader</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 410<br> <font color=#FF0000>(6/15/02 7:15:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub96.ezboard.com/fkanebaylecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=383.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The joy of finding a group.  </span><hr size=1> Want my lousy opinion? The game world is too bloody big already. VI has outdone themselves. <br><br>They started at - Virtual Monopoly - only UO was a serious competitor - Servers were all busting at the gut with over 2500 populations during peak, only had level 50 and the old world... overcrowding everywhere.<br><br>No lie - on Sol Ro in L Guk there was usually 75+ people and weekends saw 100+ during peak... SolB was usually about 20 people less.<br><br>Anyways, Kunark opened up the world ALOT. For both high end (51+) and lower levels. It really grew the world by X2 (or more, mayby someone knows the exact ratios).<br><br>In my opinion - the world was good there. Mayby add a few more plains (like they did), but there was no need for Velious, Luclin, or the upcoming Planes expansion.<br><br>The balance of players to zones was good at Kunark. <br><br>However, from a business standpoint, VI needs to feed their families and Porche gastanks, and thus has added all this (sometimes clever and well done) additional content. But look where it has got us - underpopulated, deserted zones. <br><br>The world is too big - and it's going to get bigger with the Planes thing.<br><br>But that's all she wrote - after that its EQ2 and Star Wars... the only question is - how many hardcore EQ players will continue to play the old EQ and for how long - after all there will be no char or gear xfers and another thing - look at the incredibly old and antiquated UO - still going strong.<br><br>I wouldn't be surprised if EQ (not including EQ2) where still around in 2010.  <p><center>http://www.kanebayle.com</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub96.ezboard.com/ucerosofvazaelle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ceros of Vazaelle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Level 30, Heck Level Poster</span><br>  Posts: 92<br> <font color=#FF0000>(6/15/02 7:45:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub96.ezboard.com/fkanebaylecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=383.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The joy of finding a group.  </span><hr size=1> I don't think it's fair to say that the only reason to add content is to pad SOE bank accounts.  <br><br>I mean, clearly, they're only going to release a product if it has money making potential, but I think that the vast majority of players also want new content and different areas to explore.  ..and, they've all been successful, popular and fun.  SoV was by far the most fun I've ever had in EQ.  Luclin's raid time sinks suck, but you can't argue with the success of the exp zones.<br><br>I do agree with you that the population *feels* far too spread out now, and I have ranted quite a bit about how I miss the original game where just about every zone was buzzing with activity.<br><br>Still, most players do converge in popular exp areas, and once you get more porters, lfg should be enough to get people together, despite an expansive world.  Factor in Luclin ports and firepot binding, and the world has never been easier to travel in. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub96.ezboard.com/usllackblader.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sllack Blader</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WID